Western capitalism operates within a broken incentive system in which the benefits of immigration are private and the costs public, so that even when the costs massively outweigh the benefits, private actors are misaligned with the realistic calculus. ...
... The most convenient (but extremely sloppy) remedy would require simply overriding private interests in low quality immigration in the name of the public good, but ...

... this passes the problem to the other side of Scylla and Charybdis, because politicians have their own narrow incentives, based on electoral calculations which are equally -- if not even more extremely -- divorced from any objective estimation of population quality.
